  ('Drop-Step Crossover Go on Cue', 'drop-step-crossover-go-on-cue', 'The athlete waits for a live cue (visual side cue), selects the correct answer, performs the movement response, and resets before the next rep. The rep counts only when the athlete reacts to the real stimulus rather than guessing early.', 'INTERMEDIATE', 8, 4, 4, 8, 60, 68, 'Drop-Step Crossover Go on Cue is a reaction-time-reduction drill for fast hip reorientation and crossover response. Use it when the goal is faster stimulus recognition, cleaner first movement, and safer reset behavior without turning reaction work into conditioning.', 'Primary subrole: deceleration_cod_power. Coach Drop-Step Crossover Go on Cue as a quality-first reaction drill: define the cue, remove ambiguous starts, require a clean answer, and rest long enough that speed, accuracy, posture, and safety stay intact.', 'See the cue, answer fast, finish clean, then reset. Do not guess before the signal.', 'Reactive Change of Direction, Braking, and Re-Acceleration', 'output', 'deceleration_cod_power', 'drop_step_crossover_go_on_cue', '{"stimulus":"visual side cue","decision_pattern":"drop-step, crossover, and drive","space_needed":"Clear lane, small grid, or box with safe stopping room and no crossing traffic.","setup":"Mark start, finish/reset area, and any target lanes. Explain valid cues and decoy cues before the first rep. Rehearse once at low speed, then randomize the cue.","primary_joint_actions":["hip_flexion_extension","ankle_stiffness","trunk_bracing"],"primary_tissues":["calves","quadriceps","glutes","adductors","core"],"primary_motor_control_demands":["stimulus_discrimination","response_inhibition","first_step_timing","postural_reset"],"postural_shape":null,"breathing_demand":"brief brace with relaxed reset breathing","balance_demand":"dynamic balance during reaction and reset","coordination_demand":"high cue-to-action coordination","impact_level":2,"quality_gate":"Rep counts only when the athlete waits for the valid